Article.Abstract: Immune responses to the factor IX protein pose problems for hemophilia B patients who develop antibodies against factor IX and for potential future treatment with gene therapy. To better define the response to human factor IX, we analyzed T-cell responses to human factor IX in factor IX knockout mice on BALB/c and C57BL/6 (B6) backgrounds, both strains having CD4+ T cells that proliferate in response to human factor IX. Surprisingly, wild-type mice have similar factor IX-recognizing CD4+ T cells. We defined a dominant CD4+ epitope for each strain (CVETGVKITVVAGEH for BALB/c and LLELDEPLVLNSYVTPIC for B6) that was recognized by both factor IX knockout and wild-type mice. While human factor IX did not cross-react with the mouse homologs of these epitopes, immunization with peptides from murine factor IX stimulated proliferation in factor IX knockout mice and wild-type mice, demonstrating a failure to delete murine factor IX-specific T cells in normal mice.
Article.ArticleTitle: Identification of T-cell epitopes in clotting factor IX and lack of tolerance in inbred mice.

Epitope.EpitopeComments: This peptide, from human coagulation Factor IX, was demonstrated to be the optimal epitope by truncation analysis of the response agaisnt peptide hFIX 265-282 (AAHCVETGVKITVVAGEH), which was most effective - from 75 overlapping peptides spanning the complete protein sequence - at inducing T cell proliferation in BALB/c mice (both WT or endogenous Factor IX knock-out) after immunization with the human protein. The Swiss-prot entry is for Factor IX precursor, containing Coagulation factor IXa light chain and Coagulation factor Ixa heavy chain. A.k.a. Christmas factor and Plasma thromboplastin component (PTC).

Immunization.ImmunizationComments: 9-10 days after immunization, draining popliteal lymph node were removed. This protocol is not explicitly detailed for peptide immunizations, but is the one used for whole protein immunizations in the same article. The carrier was composed of hFIX 265-282.

AssayInformation.AssayComments: In Factor IX knock-out BALB/c mice immunized with peptide hFIX 265-282 (AAHCVETGVKITVVAGEH), a proliferative response against the peptide is seen, as well as against the human Factor IX protein. In contrast, no proliferation is seen against the murine homologue peptide, mFIX 263-280 (AAHCLKPGDKIEVVAGEY), which differs in 6 residues with the human counterpart.

Immunization.ImmunizationComments: 9-10 days after immunization, draining popliteal lymph node were removed.

AssayInformation.AssayComments: 10 BALB/c mice and 6 endogenous Factor IX knock-out mice backcrossed on a BALB/c background, immunized with human Factor IX similarly recognize peptide hFIX 265-282 (AAHCVETGVKITVVAGEH) as the most (of 75 overlapping peptide spanning the whole protein sequence) able to stimulate T cell proliferation. Subsequently truncated peptides were used to determine this minimal epitope as the responsible for proliferation in Factor IX knock-out mice. Proliferation in response to the whole protein had been shown to be mainly due to CD4+ cells, but the phenotype was not assessed on peptide-induced proliferating cells.

Epitope.EpitopeComments: This peptide is immunogenic in BALB/c source protein knock-out mice. The Swiss-prot entry is for Factor IX precursor, containing Coagulation factor IXa light chain and Coagulation factor Ixa heavy chain. A.k.a. Christmas factor.

Immunization.ImmunizationComments: 9-10 days after immunization, draining popliteal lymph node were removed. This protocol is not explicitly detailed for peptide immunizations, but is the one used for whole protein immunizations in the same article.

AssayInformation.AssayComments: In Factor IX knock-out BALB/c mice immunized with peptide a proliferative response against the peptide is seen. In contrast, no proliferation is seen against the human homologue peptide, hFIX 265-282 (AAHCVETGVKITVVAGEH), which differs in 6 residues with the mouse counterpart, nor against the human Factor IX protein. This shows that the lack of reponse against this peptide in mice immunized with the human protein or peptide is not due to a lack of reponding T cells, but to a lack of cross-reactivity in the response.

AssayInformation.AssayComments: In B6 mice immunized with peptide a proliferative response against the peptide is seen. Proliferation, albeit lower, is seen against the human homologue peptide, hFIX 319-336 (LLELDEPLVLNSYVTPIC), which differs in 2 residues with the mouse counterpart, but not against the human Factor IX protein. Also, it confirms that in normal mice the cells that respond to mouse factor IX sequences are neither deleted nor anergized.
